note: Justin Herbert is the QB11 in fantasy points per game. Last week's QB4 performance in weekly scoring was his first QB1 outing since Week 9. It was the first time that he had passed for at least 300 yards since Week 7. Among 45 qualifying quarterbacks, Herbert ranks 14th in yards per attempt, fifth in passing touchdowns (tied), sixth in highly accurate throw rate, and 12th in hero throw rate. I'll be surprised if he finishes as a QB1 this week against Houston's nasty pass defense. Since Week 12, Houston has allowed the 12th-fewest yards per attempt, the eighth-lowest passer rating, and the tenth-fewest passing yards per game while generating the fifth-best pressure rate.

C.J. Stroud is the QB21 in fantasy points per game with three QB1 outings this season. I thought he could squeak out another last week against the Raiders, but Stroud disappointed with only 187 passing yards, one passing touchdown, and 5.3 yards per attempt. That was the third time this season that he has been held under 200 yards passing. Among 45 qualifying quarterbacks, Stroud ranks 19th in passing yards per game and yards per attempt, 31st in highly accurate throw rate, and 28th in hero throw rate. This looks like another low-end QB2 week for Stroud. Since Week 12, Los Angeles has ranked 15th in yards per attempt while allowing the fourth-fewest passing touchdowns, the third-lowest passer rating, and the 13th-lowest CPOE.

Malik Willis came off the bench last week and nearly led Green Bay to a win. He sustained a shoulder injury last week. He's a coin flip to play this week. We also need to know Jordan Love's status (concussion protocol) before determining the outlook for Willis for Week 17.

Tyler Huntley will draw the start for Baltimore this week. Last week, he filled in admirably for Lamar Jackson, completing nine of ten passes with 6.5 yards per attempt. In his only start this season, Huntley finished as the QB16 in weekly scoring, completing 77.3% of his passes with 186 yards through the air, one passing touchdown, eight carries, and 53 rushing yards. This season, Huntley has had only a 6.7 aDOT, which has helped his accuracy numbers, but he has still mustered solid marks with an 80.9% catchable target rate and a 4.3% hero throw rate. Huntley is a QB2 that could flirt with QB1 production this week against a downgraded Green Bay pass defense. Since Week 12, Green Bay has allowed the 11th-most yards per attempt, the fourth-most passing touchdowns (tied), and the 13th-highest CPOE.

Last week, with Kimani Vidal injured, Omarion Hampton saw his snap rate increase to 53.2% with a 33% route share and a 6.9% target share. Hampton finished with 17 touches and 95 total yards. Since his Week 14 return, Hampton has averaged 16 touches and 75.6 total yards. Since Week 14, Hampton has generated a wonderful 9.1% explosive run rate, but he has only had a 14% missed tackle rate and 1.50 yards after contact per attempt. With many runs, unless he can find daylight, he's simply getting what is blocked. Hampton could produce as a solid RB2 this week despite the tough matchup with his volume and touchdown equity in the offense. Since Week 12, Houston has allowed the 14th-fewest rushing yards per game, the eighth-lowest explosive run rate, and the fourth-lowest missed tackle rate.

Woody Marks is set to return to his workhorse role this week. His ankle has improved, as evidenced by his full practices all week. In Weeks 10-14, Marks averaged 20 touches and 68.8 total yards as Houston's lead back. Among 48 qualifying backs, he ranks 31st in explosive run rate and 36th in yards after contact per attempt. Those paltry rankings in per-touch efficiency highlight the continuing fact that Marks is a volume-based RB2 play. Sadly, he returns just in time to face an improved Chargers run defense. Since Week 12, the Chargers have allowed the fourth-lowest explosive run rate, the lowest yards after contact per attempt, and the second-lowest rushing success rate. Marks could still post RB2 numbers this week if he sees his customary 15-20 touches and gets in the end zone, but he won't finish with a pretty stat line.

Zay Flowers is the WR17 in fantasy points per game with a 27.6% target share, 69.5 receiving yards per game, 2.48 yards per route run, and a 33.2% first-read share. Flowers has been awesome this year. If he had scored more than two touchdowns this season, his fantasy standing would be even better. He has only eight red zone targets and has drawn 17 deep targets. Since Week 12, Green Bay has had the fourth-highest two-high rate (63.7%). Against two high, his numbers have dipped some, but remain strong with a 25% target share, 1.95 yards per route run, and a 31.7% first-read share. Flowers' ceiling and floor will be impacted this week, depending upon who is under center, but he should still be the clear focal point for the passing attack against a slipping Green Bay pass defense. Since Week 10, the Packers have allowed the fourth-most PPR points per target and the 11th-most receiving yards per game to perimeter wide receivers.

Ladd McConkey is the WR32 in fantasy points per game. Since Week 8, he has had four top 24 weekly finishes. Since Week 12, Houston has utilized single high at the second-highest rate (63%). Since Week 8, against single high, McConkey has led the team with a 20.8% target share with 1.94 yards per route run and a 15.9% first-read share. McConkey will have a tough time this week against Jalen Pitre in the slot. Since his Week 13 return, Pitre has allowed only a 45.5% catch rate and 26.3 passer rating in slot coverage. Since Week 13, Houston has allowed the 14th-fewest fantasy points per game to slot receivers. McConkey is a WR3/flex this week.

Last week, Christian Watson returned to the lineup with a 67.7% route share, a 25% target share, and a 26.3% first-read share. Watson was running wide open on multiple occasions last week and had numerous missed opportunities. It could have been a huge game for him, but sadly, it didn't work out that way as he finished with two receptions and 17 receiving yards. Watson's target volume remains a concern this week, but he should lead the Green Bay passing attack and has the big play upside to get the job done with limited volume. Since Week 11, Watson has been the WR20 in fantasy points per game with six red zone targets and a team-leading ten deep targets. Since Week 11, Baltimore has had the second-highest single high rate in the NFL (60.8%). Since Week 11, against single high, Watson has led the team with a 24.5% target share, 2.53 yards per route run, and a 32.1% first-read share. The Ravens have had issues defending perimeter wide receivers, which also helps Watson's case. Since Week 12, Baltimore has allowed the seventh-most fantasy points per game and the second-most receiving yards per game to perimeter wide receivers.

Last week, Jayden Reed led the team with an 83.9% route share as he had a 12.5% target share, 35 receiving yards, and a 15.8% first-read share. Reed did draw two red zone targets, though. With Malik Willis under center this week and the limited passing volume that is sure to accompany him, I'm sitting Reed this week. Baltimore has been strong against slot receivers. Since Week 12, they have allowed the ninth-fewest fantasy points per game and the 13th-fewest receiving yards per game to the position.

Quentin Johnston ripped Dallas apart last week as the WR11 in weekly scoring with 104 receiving yards and a score. Overall, Johnston is the WR29 in fantasy points per game with six top 24 weekly scoring finishes. Since Week 12, Houston has utilized single high at the second-highest rate (63%). Against single high, Johnston has ranked third on the team with an 18.6% target share, tied for first on the team with 1.73 yards per route run, and had a 22.8% first-read share (second on the team). Johnston should fight with Keenan Allen for the team lead in targets this week. The horrible matchup makes him only a flex play this week, though. Since Week 10, Houston has allowed the eighth-fewest fantasy points per game and the fifth-fewest receiving yards per game to perimeter wide receivers.

Keenan Allen's production has fallen off the table since Week 7. He hasn't had more than 9.3 PPR points or 53 receiving yards in any game since. Since Week 12, Houston has utilized single high at the second-highest rate (63%). Since Week 8, against single high, Allen has had only a 16.8% target share with 1.53 yards per route run and a team-leading 23.2% first-read share. Justin Herbert could look his way early and often in this game, but it's fair to question how effective Allen will be. Allen is a low-end flex play only. Since Week 10, Houston has allowed the eighth-fewest fantasy points per game and the fifth-fewest receiving yards per game to perimeter wide receivers.

Last week, Romeo Doubs had a 25% target share and 26.3% first-read share that he turned into 84 receiving yards and a touchdown. Sadly, his route share dipped to 54.8%, and his 35% target per route run rate last week is unsustainable. Doubs could have a decent game this week against a pass defense that has struggled against perimeter wide receivers, but the coverage matchup isn't in his favor. Since Week 11, Baltimore has had the second-highest single high rate in the NFL (60.8%). Since Week 11, against single high, Doubs has had an 11.7% target share, 1.29 yards per route run, and a 13.2% first-read share. Those aren't encouraging numbers at all. It does work in his favor that since Week 12, Baltimore has allowed the seventh-most fantasy points per game and the second-most receiving yards per game to perimeter wide receivers. Doubs is a deep league flex only.

It's impossible to trust Jayden Higgins as a flex play this week. Higgins has disappointed in each of the last three weeks with nice matchups. Yes, this is partially a CJ Stroud issue, but also Dalton Schultz is the clear WR2 in this offense. Higgins hasn't had more than three receptions or 34 receiving yards in a game since Week 13. This week, he faces a Bolts' pass defense that has allowed the eighth-fewest receiving yards per game and the fourth-fewest PPR points per target to perimeter wide receivers. Sit Higgins.

Since Week 3, Dalton Schultz has been the TE8 in fantasy points per game with an 18.5% target share, 48.3 receiving yards per game, 1.60 yards per route run, and an 18.7% first-read share. In those 13 games, Schultz has had three touchdowns, nine red zone targets, and five deep targets. CJ Stroud should lean on Schultz this week. Since Week 10, the Bolts have allowed the fourth-highest yards per target to tight ends while ranking 17th in fantasy points per game.

After seeing his route share dip in Week 15, last week, Oronde Gadsden saw his route share sit at 69.7%. Since Week 6, Gadsden has been the TE17 in fantasy points per game with a 15.8% target share, 53.3 receiving yards per game, 1.98 yards per route run, and a 17.7% first-read share. In those ten games, he has ten red zone targets, two touchdowns, and eight deep targets. Gadsden is back on the streaming radar this week. Since Week 10, Houston has allowed the 11th-most fantasy points per game to tight ends while ranking 17th in yards per target.

Mark Andrews' 2025 season has been an utter disappointment as the TE23 in fantasy points per game. He has a 15.9% target share with 25.3 receiving yards per game, 1.31 yards per route run, and a 19.9% first-read share. Andrews has had 13 red zone targets and two deep targets. He hasn't surpassed 50 receiving yards in a game since Week 3, and that was the only time he has done so this season. Andrews is a sit again this week. Since Week 10, Green Bay has allowed the fewest fantasy points per game and the fifth-fewest yards per target to tight ends.

Will Anderson showed up in Week 16, posting two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Anderson finally got back on track after failing to record a sack in three consecutive contests. Continue to treat Will Anderson as a top-10 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Aidan Hutchinson was excellent in Week 16, racking up three solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Aidan is up to 11.5 sacks, with three of them coming in his last two games. Tap Hutchinson as a top-12 option for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the Minnesota Vikings.

Brian Burns was excellent in Week 16, stacking two solos, two assists, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Burns is up to a career high 15 sacks and will be looking to add more to his ledger this weekend against the Las Vegas Raiders. Fire him up as a DL1 option everywhere.

Montez Sweat was at it again in Week 16, generating two solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Sweat has been one of the hottest pass rushers in the league in terms of consistency since Week 7, recording at least one sack in seven of his last 10 games.

Tuli Tuipulotu was at it again in Week 16, reeling off two solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Tuli is up to 13 sacks on the season, which ties him for third in the league. Fire Tuipulotu up as a top-10 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Rousseau showed up again in Week 16, tallying two solos, one assist, 2.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. The Bills' edge rusher is up to 6.5 sacks on the season, finally inching his way back to respectability. Rousseau's 2025 IDP campaign had been one of the most disappointing from someone formerly considered one of the best at the position. Prior to Week 15, Rousseau had just 3.5 sacks despite playing 65 to 75 percent of the snaps every week. Now, with 3.5 sacks in his last two games, we can count the defensive end as part of the top-25 conversation for a plus matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Chase Young was at it again in Week 16, tallying one solo, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Now up to seven sacks in 10 games, Young is just one sack away from setting a new career high. Chase has registered a sack in four of his last five games and in six of his last eight. It has been an impressive resurgence for the former top prospect who may finally be getting his career on track after multiple injuries threatened to derail what could have been a Hall of Fame caliber run. Start Young everywhere ahead of a tantalizing Week 17 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Laiatu Latu was at it again in Week 16, tallying three solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Latu is up to 7.5 sacks on the season, with a sack in each of his last two games. Tap Latu as a top-25 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Jalen Redmond was excellent in Week 16, racking up one solo, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Redmond has worked his way into the DL3 conversation with his steady IDP production and is now up to a strong six sacks on the season, with a sack in two of his last three. Tap Redmond as DT1/DL3 play wherever needed for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Detroit Lions on Christmas Day.

Derrick Brown was at it again in Week 16, posting three solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Brown has started to heat up at the right time for fantasy managers, recording a sack in two of his last three games. Tap the talented defensive lineman as an upside DT3/flex option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Kobie went off on Thursday night, stacking one solo, two assists, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, one interception, and two passes usually. We don't normally suggest players rostered in 10 percent or more of Yahoo leagues, but his rostership numbers suggest that he is still available in more than a few competitive leagues. Turner is up to seven sacks on the season, with 5.5 of them coming in four of his last five games. Fire Kobie up as a DL2 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Jordan Davis showed up in Week 16, tallying four solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. Davis has picked it back up in the solo department enough to put him on flex2 radars for Week 17, even for those in 12-team leagues. Tap the Eagles' defensive tackle where needed for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Cam Jordan was at it again in Week 16, posting four solos, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. Jordan is up to an impressive 8.5 sacks, which ties him for his most sacks since 2022. The ageless veteran has registered a sack in four of his last six contests, totaling six sacks in that span. Fire Jordan up as an upside DL2 play for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Jonathan Allen showed up in Week 16, notching four solos, four assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Allen is up to a solid 3.5 sacks, but should only be considered a Week 17 option for those in DT leagues. Look elsewhere for championship week.

Dre'Mont showed up in Week 16, stacking two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Jones is up to seven sacks on the season, but has just 2.5 sacks since joining the Ravens in Week 10. Tap Dre'Mont as a DL3 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Keeanu Benton was excellent in Week 16, posting two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Benton is up to an impressive 5.5 sacks, which makes him a flex option in 20+ team DL leagues and as an elite DT2 in DT leagues. Tap Keeanu where needed for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

John Franklin-Myers showed up in Week 16, tallying two solos, one assist, two sacks, and one tackle for loss. Franklin-Myers has snuck his way up to a career high 7.5 sacks and makes for a solid flex/flex2 option for those in 12-team leagues. Start JFM where needed for a tasty Week 17 matchup against a tattered Kansas City Chiefs offense.

Chauncey Golston showed up in Week 16, tallying four solos, two assists, one sack, and three tackles for loss. Golston got extra burn with Kayvon Thibodeaux done for the season and is worth a look in 32-team DT leagues. With that said, those in 12-team leagues should leave him on the waiver wire.

D.J. Jones was excellent in Week 16, racking up four solos, three assists, one sack, and one pass defended. Jones has just three sacks on the season and is not a fantasy option, even for those in ocean-deep DT leagues. Look elsewhere for championship week.

Truman Jones (LB/DE - TEN) SIT
Truman Jones showed up in Week 16, racking up two solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Truman saw an expanded role with the Titans thin at linebacker and likely made enough of an impression to get another look on defense. With that said, Jones is an ocean deep league stash only and should not be started in leagues of any size under any circumstances. Look elsewhere for Week 17.

Jordyn Brooks was at it again in Week 16, notching five solos, nine assists, and one pass defended. Brooks has been elite all season and leads the NFL in solo and total tackles. Fire him up as a top-three option for championship week.

Roquan Smith was excellent in Week 16, tallying eight solos and two assists against the New England Patriots on Sunday Night Football. Roquan has been as steady as they come at the position for years, and that has not changed in 2025 despite the Baltimore Ravens' struggles on both sides of the ball. Tap Smith as a top-five option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Blake Cashman was at it again in Week 16, tallying seven solos and nine assists. Cashman has been an easy LB1 play when he has been healthy this season and should be counted as one for championship week despite the neutral on-paper matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Jack Campbell was at it again in Week 16, reeling off seven solos, nine assists, one fumble recovery, and two passes defended. Campbell has been an elite LB1 option all season, and that will not change in Week 17 with a plus matchup on tap against Minnesota. Start Campbell everywhere.

Wagner was at it again in Week 16, tallying five solos, five assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Wagner has been a steady LB1 force all season, but just posted his most productive three game stretch of the season. Fire the veteran linebacker up as a top-10 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys on Christmas Day.

Carson Schwesinger was at it again in Week 16, notching five solos, nine assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Carson has bullied his way into the LB1 conversation since the Browns' Week 9 bye and should be treated as a top-15 option for Week 17 despite the neutral-at-best matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Start Schwesinger everywhere.

Foye was excellent in Week 16, racking up six solos and five assists. Oluokun has slipped to the LB2 realm but is still one of the better IDP options at the position. Treat him as such for a plus Week 17 matchup against Philip Rivers and the Indianapolis Colts.

Devin White was at it again in Week 16, posting seven solos, four assists, and one pass defended. White is back to his early season LB1 form and should be treated as a top-15 option for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the New York Giants. Start Devin everywhere.

Ernest Jones stayed hot in Week 16, tallying four solos, eight assists, and one tackle for loss. Jones is an easy LB1 play for Week 17 despite the neutral-at-best on paper matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Jamien Sherwood was elite in Week 16, racking up seven solos, four assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Sherwood has been part of the top-15 conversation for most of the season, but has really stepped it up over his last three outings. Treat Jamien as an LB1 option for Week 17, thanks to his recent production and the plus matchup against the New England Patriots.

T.J. Edwards was excellent in Week 16, reeling off five solos, five assists, and 0.5 sacks. Edwards has dealt with the injury bug for multiple stretches this season, but has now posted five solos in back-to-back outings, making him a strong LB2 pay for a plus Week 17 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Nick Bolton stayed hot in Week 16, tallying four solos, six assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Bolton has forced his way back into the LB1 conversation, and his elite production could not have come at a better time for fantasy managers. Fire him up as a top-12 option for Week 17 despite a neutral-at-best matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Alex Singleton was excellent in Week 16, posting four solos and nine assists. Singleton has been a disappointment for much of the season, but has still posted steady enough numbers most weeks. With that said, the disappointment is relative to expectations, which were sky high for the Broncos' linebacker. Tap Singleton as an upside LB3 play for Week 17 against the Kansas City Chiefs on Christmas Day.

Bobby Okereke was excellent in Week 16, racking up seven solos, six assists, and one pass defended. Okereke is an easy top-20 play for Week 17, thanks to a plus matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders. Start him everywhere.

Quay Walker was excellent in Week 16, racking up five solos, nine assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Quay makes for a strong LB2 play for Week 17, thanks to a plus matchup against the Baltimore Ravens. Start Walker where needed.

Nate Landman was excellent in Week 16, racking up two solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Landman has been an LB1 force for fantasy managers this season and should continue to be treated as one for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons on Monday Night Football.

Quincy Williams stayed hot in Week 17, racking up six solos and five assists. Williams has been part of the top-15 conversation since reasserting himself in Week 10 and should be treated as such for a plus Week 17 matchup against the New England Patriots. There is no reason for Quincy to be available in any competitive leagues.

Lavonte was excellent in Week 16, racking up six solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. David has slipped to the low end of the LB2 conversation since the Buccaneers Week 9 bye and should continue to be viewed as such for Week 17 despite the plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Christian Rozeboom was excellent in Week 16, racking up three solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Rozeboom has posted plus outings in back-to-back games but remains a flex/flex2 as opposed to an LB3. With that said, he absolutely has a place in starting lineups for Week 17 in 11 v 11 leagues. Start Rozeboom everywhere.

Milano was excellent in Week 16, notching four solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. The veteran followed up an elite splash week with his second spike week of the season and looks to have heated up at the right time for fantasy managers. Tap Milano as an LB3 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Akeem Davis-Gaither showed up in Week 16, notching five solos and six assists. ADG has worked his way back into the LB3 conversation over his last three games and can be counted as one for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Barrett Carter showed up in Week 16, tallying one solo, four assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Carter has struggled in the solo department and should probably be left on benches where at all possible for Week 17 despite the plus matchup against the Arizona Cardinals. Look elsewhere for championship week.

SirVocea showed up in Week 16, notching six solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Dennis was an easy LB2 play prior to the Buccaneers Week 9 bye, but has slipped to the LB3/flex conversation since. Treat him as such for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Drake Thomas got back on track in Week 16, racking up six solos and seven assists. Thomas flirted with top-15 value for most of his tenure as the Seahawks starter beside Ernest Jones, but slipped to low-end LB2 status after some down weeks. Mercifully, the talented linebacker looks like he is ready for another productive stretch after recording his first game with more than three solos since Week 12. Tap Thomas as a top-25 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Troy Dye will get the start this week with Denzel Perryman suspended for the final two games of the season. Dye filled in admirably earlier this season when Perryman was sidelined, particularly during a three game span from Week 4 to Week 6, where he checked in as the LB12 in fppg. Tap Dye as an LB3/flex option in leagues of all sizes for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Trenton Simpson showed up in Week 15, tallying six solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Simpson saw an expanded role with Teddye Buchanan sidelined and could get another spot start in Week 17. Simpson is more of a flex play, even if he gets the start, but will offer more upside than most other options. Make the speculative add where possible ahead of a plus matchup against the Green Bay Packers in Week 17.

AVG was excellent in Week 16, racking up two solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Van Ginkel is up to five sacks on the season, with 3.5 of them coming in his last six games. AVG has posted at least a half sack in four of his last six games and makes for an upside flex option for Week 17 against Detroit.

Alex Highsmith showed up in Week 16, tallying four solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. Highsmith has 6.5 sacks on the season, but may find less room to operate with both T.J. Watt and Nick Herbig dealing with injuries. Tap the Steelers edge rusher as a DL3 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Kyle Hamilton was excellent in Week 16, posting five solos, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Hamilton has been a disappointment relative to expectations this season, but is still a solid DB1 option due to his weekly upside. Treat him as a low-end DB1 for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Budda Baker was excellent in Week 16, racking up four solos, six assists, and one pass defended. Baker has been a massive IDP disappointment this season, but has started to make an impact over his last five contests, providing four plus outings. Tap Budda as a top-25 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Derwin James was excellent in Week 16, tallying five solos, one assist, and one forced fumble. Derwin hasn't quite been the IDP force he has been in past seasons, but his upside still keeps him in the top-20 conversation. Treat him as such for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Jordan Battle stayed hot in Week 16, racking up six solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. Battle has been on fire for fantasy managers, checking in as the DB6 in fppg since Week 13. Start Battle with confidence as a top-15 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Nick Emmanwori stayed hot in Week 16, tallying seven solos and four assists. The rookie safety has forced his way into the DB1 conversation with his excellent production and should be treated as a top-15 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Kevin Byard showed up in Week 16, reeling off five solos and four assists. Byard has recorded five or more solos in two of his last three games and four or more in seven of his last nine. Tap Byard as a borderline DB2 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

Chamarri made an impact in Week 16, tallying six solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Chamarri has caught fire for fantasy managers down the stretch, providing at least DB2 level production in four of his last six contests. Tap Conner as a top-25 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Jalen Pitre showed up in Week 16, racking up six solos, one assist, and one pass defended. Pitre has now posted plus outings in two of his last three games, putting him in the DB3/flex mix for Week 17 against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Devon Witherspoon was back at it in Week 16, reeling off five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Devon has been in his DB3 bag over the last three weeks, and can be counted as a top-36 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Cam Bynum was excellent in Week 16, posting five solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Bynum has put together plus outings in three of his last four games and can be counted as a top-20 option for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars. Start Cam in all competitive leagues.

Cooper DeJean was excellent in Week 16, posting five solos, one interception, and four passes defended. DeJean slipped to the DB3 realm after a scorching start to the season and should continue to be viewed as one despite the standout performance against Washington. Tap Cooper as an upside DB3 play for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Marlon Humphrey was excellent in Week 16, posting six solos, one interception, and two passes defended. Humphrey has really turned it on since Week 9, checking as the DB1 in fppg during that timeframe. Tap Humphrey as an elite DB1 with obvious DB1 upside for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Kyle Dugger showed up in Week 16, notching six solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Dugger had been quiet since Week 11, so this outing will help keep fantasy managers confident in his production heading into championship week. Tap Dugger as a DB3/4 where needed for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Alontae Taylor showed up in Week 16, racking up five solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Alontae has been inconsistent this season but continues to flash his DB2 form. Treat Taylor as an upside DB3 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Kamari Lassiter was at it again in Week 16, tallying four solos, four assists, and two passes defended. The DB3 in fppg since Week 7, Lassiter should be counted as an elite DB2 option for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Malachi Moore was excellent in Week 16, tallying five solos, three assists, and one forced fumble. Moore continues to ascend and has seemingly cemented himself as a DB2 option thanks to plus outings in three of his last five games. Malachi has been producing at a steady DB2 level and should be treated as such for a plus Week 17 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Nubin showed up again in Week 16, racking up four solos, two assists, one fumble recovery, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Nubin has shown flashes but has been inconsistent as an IDP option due to limited contributions in the peripherals. Now the author of season high fantasy outputs in consecutive weeks, Nubin can be tapped as a DB3/4 for championship week. Add and start him everywhere for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Riley Moss stepped up in Week 16, stacking five solos, one assist, one sack, two tackles for loss, and two passes defended. Moss has posted back-to-back spike weeks and is firmly back on the map as a top-36 option. Moss spent weeks as a locked-in DB2 play earlier in the season, but should be treated as an elite DB3 play for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the husk of the Kansas City Chiefs.

Dadrion Taylor-Demerson showed up in Week 16, racking five solos, six assists, and one pass defended on 97 percent of the snaps. DTD could get another start this week with Jalen Thompson dealing with a hamstring injury, putting him on the deep league flex radar. Start Dadrion where needed if he indeed gets another start.

Scott was at it again in Week 16, shocking fantasy managers with nine solos and one assist. This is now three straight plus outings for Scott, who, for most of his career, was viewed as not having enough upside to even warrant a roster spot in IDP. Scott has obviously heated up for the Panthers and can be trusted as an elite DB3/flex where needed for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

D.J. Reed showed up in Week 16, racking up seven solos and one assist. Reed has posted plus outings in two of his last three games, putting him on the radar for Week 17, even in DB leagues. Tap Reed as a DB4/flex option for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the Minnesota Timberwolves.

Jonas Sanker showed up in Week 16, tallying one solo, five assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Sanker looked to be on his way to steady DB3 value earlier in the season, but has become more emergency bench depth due to his near bottomless floor. Look elsewhere for Week 17.

Alohi Gilman continued his strong play in Week 16, posting six solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Gilman has burst back into the DB2/3 conversation now that he is comfortable with the Ravens defense and should be started with confidence for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Ji'Ayir Brown was excellent in Week 15, tallying five solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Brown has flashed with two plus outings and one splash week in his last five contests, moving him from flex territory back into the DB3 realm. Treat him as a low floor DB3 for a plus Week 17 matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Javon Bullard showed up in Week 16, racking up five solos, five assists, and one pass defended. Bullard has been nothing more than bench depth for most of the season despite promising upside. Look elsewhere for Week 17 despite the strong production against Chicago.

Christian Gonzalez was back at it in Week 16, recording seven solos and one pass defended. Gonzalez is an elite talent on the field, but it does not always translate for IDP purposes, as opposing quarterbacks often look elsewhere when possible. He can pile up the solo count in plus matchups, however, and has another one on tap for Week 17 against the New York Jets. Treat Christian as a DB4/flex.

James Williams stepped in and stopped up in Week 16, making waves with eight solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 100 percent of the snaps. Williams, primarily a special teamer, got the tap with Cedric Gray sidelined. Williams has registered 12 solos in his last two games, but had just two total in the rest of his games this season. Stash the linebacker where possible, as he looks like a must-start LB3 if Cedric Gray misses another game. Add and start Williams as a potential difference maker for a tasty Week 17 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Thomas Harper was excellent in Week 16, racking up four solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Harper has provided strong flex value when getting spot starts over the last few weeks and can be plugged into lineups in deeper leagues if he gets the call again on the short week.

Kristian Fulton showed up in Week 16, registering seven solos and three assists. Fulton has been inactive for most of the season and should not be trusted for Week 17. Look elsewhere for championship week.

Stingley showed up in Week 16, racking up one solo, one assist, one forced fumble, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Stingley, like most elite corners, is more of a CB league option than someone you want to be using in 12-team DB leagues. Look elsewhere for championship week.

C.J. Henderson showed up in Week 16, notching three solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Henderson, a former first round pick, has spent the season on the practice squad and is not a Week 17 fantasy option under any circumstances. Look elsewhere for championship week.

Shavon Revel Jr. showed up in Week 16, reeling off eight solos, one assist, and one pass defended. Revel has provided steady CB2/flex2 value over the last three weeks and can be tapped as a flex2 option if you find yourself in desperation mode due to deep rosters and injury issues. Start Shavon where needed for Week 17, thanks to his recent production and a tasty Week 17 matchup against Washington.
